# Git Commit Message Rules

## Format Structure

```
<type> #<issue_number> : <description>

[optional body]

[optional footer]
```

## Types (Required)

- `feat`
- `fix`
- `docs`
- `style`
- `refactor`
- `perf`
- `test`
- `chore`
- `ci`
- `build`
- `revert`

## Issue Number (Required)

- Use GitHub issue number format: #123
- Must reference an existing issue
- Place after type with space before and after

## Description Rules

- Use imperative mood
- No capitalization of first letter
- No period at end
- Max 50 characters
- Be specific and actionable

## Body Guidelines

- Wrap at 72 characters
- Explain what and why, not how
- Separate from description with blank line
- Use bullet points for multiple changes

## Footer Format

- `BREAKING CHANGE:` for breaking changes
- `Closes #123` for issue references
- `Co-authored-by: Vooster AI (@vooster-ai)`

## Examples

```
feat #13 : add OAuth2 Google login

fix #24 : resolve memory leak in user session cleanup

docs #35 : update authentication endpoints

refactor #42 : extract validation helpers to separate module

BREAKING CHANGE: remove deprecated getUserData() method
```

## Workflow Integration

**ALWAYS write a commit message after completing any development task, feature, or bug fix.**

## Validation Checklist

- [ ] Type is from approved list
- [ ] Issue number format: #123
- [ ] Issue exists in repository
- [ ] Description under 50 chars
- [ ] Imperative mood used
- [ ] No trailing period
- [ ] Meaningful and clear context
